<!-- First question -->
<section id="about" class="container content-section text-center">
  <div class="row">
    <h2>
    Can you briefly describe the history of the Ruby on Rails community in Melbourne? What were your first challenges and failures in the past?
    </h2>
  
    <hr>

    <div class="col-lg-8 col-lg-offset-2"> 
      <br>
        <p>
        There’s been Ruby/Rails meets in Melbourne for about ten years now. I started attending within that first year, having been introduced to Rails by a friend, and I was keen to learn more. Back then, there was maybe a dozen of us, and maybe only one or two actually used Ruby or Rails in their jobs.
        </p>

        <p>
        Over the years it’s grown, and now we have around 100 people attending our meets, and the majority are paid to work with Ruby. Many Melbourne Rubyists have been hosts, and currently it’s Mario Visic and I who take care of that.
        </p>

        <p>
        I’m not sure about failures, but I think we face many challenges that the technology industry faces generally - in particular, how dominated it is by white men. I’m aware we still have a long way to go, but I’m very glad that we now have a growing number of women attending. There are also challenges with ensuring we have events that appeal to all levels of Ruby experience, that we have a good mix of food to cater for all dietary requirements (and enough to feed everyone!), and that we are actively welcoming people into the community, helping them become established Rubyists.
        </p>

        <p>
        These are all things that I think we’re getting better at, but there’s plenty of room for improvement.
        </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
    
<!-- Second question -->
<section id="about" class="container content-section text-center">
  <div class="row">
    <h2>
    Ruby Nights, Hack Nights, Installfests are all Ruby meet-ups that happen in Melbourne. What are the differences between them, and why this structure? How many people usually attend each of these kinds of meet-ups?
    </h2>
    <hr>
               
    <div class="col-lg-8 col-lg-offset-2"> 
      <br>
        <p>               
			  The main event - Melbourne Ruby, or the Presentations event - is what has existed since the beginning. It’s a night where we have a few speakers present on topics related to Ruby or programming generally, and then there’s plenty of socialising before and after. These days, we’ll get 80-100 people attending.
        </p>
               
        <p>
        Our Hack Nights have only been around for about 18 months, and these events are an opportunity for people to sit down and work on some code - and if they get stuck on something, they’re surrounded by other developers who can help. It’s a great event for both beginners and experienced developers. This is a smaller event, with around 30 people each month.
        </p>
               
        <p>
        InstallFests are something that the great team at reinteractive have helped bring to Melbourne - it’s an event where beginners work through installing Ruby and Rails and building a basic blogging app for the first time. There are mentors on hand to help when anyone hits a bug or doesn’t understand something.
        </p>

        <p>
        All of these events seek to connect the community - through conversations and sharing skills - and also to provide opportunities to work on Ruby code and receive help when needed.
        </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

